library(ggplot2)
head(policy_table)
policy_table2 <- policy_table %>%
  group_by(user_id) %>%
  mutate(
    earliest_start_date = min(start_date, na.rm = TRUE),
    latest_policy_end_date = max(policy_end_date, na.rm = TRUE),
    latest_cancellation_date = max(cancellation_date, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

policy_table2$earliest_start_date <- as.Date(policy_table2$earliest_start_date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
policy_table2$latest_policy_end_date <- as.Date(policy_table2$latest_policy_end_date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
policy_table2$latest_cancellation_date <- as.Date(policy_table2$latest_cancellation_date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")


# Calculate retention_duration based on conditions
policy_table2$retention_duration <- ifelse(is.na(policy_table2$latest_cancellation_date),
                                policy_table2$latest_policy_end_date - policy_table2$earliest_start_date,
                                policy_table2$latest_cancellation_date - policy_table2$earliest_start_date)


policy_table2$retention_duration_in_weeks <- ceiling(policy_table2$retention_duration / 7)

policy_table2 <- policy_table2 %>%
  distinct(user_id, .keep_all = TRUE)

#create a histogram

# Filter data to include only retention durations up to week 52
policy_table2_filtered <- policy_table2 %>%
  filter(retention_duration_in_weeks <= 55)

ggplot(policy_table2_filtered, aes(x = retention_duration_in_weeks)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "blue", color = "black", stat = "count") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of users in different lengths of retention duration in Weeks",
    x = "Retention Duration in Weeks",
    y = "Count of User_id"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 55, by = 2)) +
  theme_minimal()

Lets conduct some exploratory analyses to identify factors associated with retention_on_after_7_months

library(ggplot2)

#given that most ofcodes for these plots will be repetitive, I create a function for ggplot for a categorical variable.
plot_retention_percentage <- function(data, x_var, y_var) {
  percentages <- data %>% #calculating percentages first
    na.omit() %>%
    group_by({{x_var}}, {{y_var}}) %>%
    summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
    group_by({{x_var}}, .drop = TRUE) %>%
    mutate(percentage = count / sum(count) * 100)
  ggplot(percentages, aes(x = {{x_var}}, y = percentage, fill = {{y_var}})) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", alpha = 0.5) +
    labs(x = deparse(substitute(x_var)), y = "Percentage", title = paste("Percentage", deparse(substitute(y_var)), "by", deparse(substitute(x_var)))) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red"), labels = c("No retention", "retention")) +
    geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(percentage), "%")), position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), vjust = -0.5, size = 3, color = "black") +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 10, face = "bold"),
      axis.title = element_text(size = 10),
      axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
      axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
      legend.title = element_blank()
    )
}

#A function for a count graph to objectively see different magnitudes of attrition in each category
plot_retention_count <- function(data, x_var, y_var) {
  counts <- data %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    group_by({{x_var}}, {{y_var}}) %>%
    summarise(count = n(), .groups = "drop")

  ggplot(counts, aes(x = {{x_var}}, y = count, fill = {{y_var}})) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge", alpha = 0.5) +
    labs(x = deparse(substitute(x_var)), y = "Count", title = paste("Count of", deparse(substitute(y_var)), "by", deparse(substitute(x_var)))) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "red"), labels = c("No retention", "retention")) +
    geom_text(aes(label = count), position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), vjust = -0.5, size = 3, color = "black") +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 10, face = "bold"),
      axis.title = element_text(size = 10),
       axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
      axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
      legend.title = element_blank()
    )
}

# Fit logistic regression model
model <- glm(retention_on_after_7_months ~ has_claims + has_violations + currently_insured + 
               currently_insured_length_months + credit_range + age_group + education + 
              + marital_status, 
             data = df, family = binomial)

# Create summary table and filter significant variables
library(knitr)
library(broom)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

summary_table <- tidy(model)
significant_vars <- summary_table %>%
  filter(p.value < 0.05) %>%
  arrange(p.value)

# Add a column for ranking the importance of each variable
significant_vars$Importance_Rank <- seq_along(significant_vars$p.value)

cat("Significant Predictors of Employee Attrition\n")
## Significant Predictors of Employee Attrition
#let's convert this into a graph to grasp it easier.
significant_vars_graph<- significant_vars %>%
  mutate(importance  = abs(statistic))


importance_barplot <- ggplot(significant_vars_graph, aes(x = importance, y = reorder(term, importance))) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "skyblue") +
  labs(x = "Importance Level (based on the size of absolute value of Z statistic)", y = "importance", title = "Important Factors in Influencing Retention after 7 Months") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1), 
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

print(importance_barplot)
